# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: buckminsterfullerene
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] In 1849, Charles Blachford Mansfield rectified coal tar and identified fractions which he hypothesized to be cumole and cymole.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] The latter fraction boiled slightly above 170 °C (338 °F) and had specific density of 0.857.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] In 1862, Warren De la Rue and Hugo Müller (1833-1915) proposed the term **pseudocumole** for the fractions heavier than xylole.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] When three years later American chemist Cyrus Warren (1824-1891) attempted to reproduce Mansfield's results, he determined that the oil boiling at 170 °C (338 °F) has the same formula as cumole, not cymole, and suggested to name it **isocumole**.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] The structure of the compound was determined by Th.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] Ernst and Wilhelm Rudolph Fittig, who first prepared it from bromoxylene and iodomethane in 1866 by a Wurtz–Fittig reaction developed two years earlier.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] In the next year, Fittig et al. adopted the pseudocumol terminology, in 1869 Fittig and B.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] Wackenroder proved that the fraction is a mixture of mesitylene with another trimethylbenzene, for which the name of pseudocumol was retained, and in 1886 Oscar Jacobsen showed that the third trimethylbenzene he discovered earlier is also present.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] Industrially, it is isolated from the C9 aromatic hydrocarbon fraction during petroleum distillation.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] Approximately 40% of this fraction is 1,2,4-trimethylbenzene.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] It is also generated by methylation of toluene and xylenes and the disproportionation of xylene over aluminosilicate catalysts.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] Pseudocumene is a precursor to trimellitic anhydride, from which high performance polymers are made.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] It is also used as a sterilizing agent and in the making of dyes, perfumes and resins.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] Another use is as an antiknock agent, since its research and motor octane numbers are well above 100.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] In automobile fuel it is a minor additive, with its share in US gasoline rising from 0.03%–0.5% in early 1990s to 1.1%–2.6% in 2011.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] It may be a major component of some avgas formulations.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] 1,2,4-Trimethylbenzene dissolved in mineral oil is used as a liquid scintillator in particle physics experiments such as NOνA and Borexino.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-dichlorobenzene] It is mainly used as a precursor chemical in the synthesis of agrochemicals, as a preferred solvent for dissolving and working with fullerenes, as an insecticide, and in softening and removing carbon-based contamination on metal surfaces.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-dichlorobenzene] The reaction also affords the 1,4- and small amounts of the 1,3-isomer.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-dichlorobenzene] The 1,4- isomer is preferred over the 1,2- isomer due to steric hindrance.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-dichlorobenzene] The 1,3- isomer is uncommon because it is a meta- compound, while chlorine, like all halogens, is an ortho/para- director in terms of electrophilic aromatic substitution.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-dichlorobenzene] It is mainly used as a precursor to 1,2-dichloro-4-nitrobenzene, an intermediate in the synthesis of agrochemicals.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-dichlorobenzene] In terms of niche applications, 1,2-dichlorobenzene is a versatile, high-boiling solvent.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-dichlorobenzene] It is a preferred solvent for dissolving and working with fullerenes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-dichlorobenzene] It is an insecticide for termites and locust borers, historically used by the United States Forest Service to combat widespread bark beetle outbreaks.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-dichlorobenzene] 1,2-Dichlorobenzene is also used in softening and removing carbon-based contamination on metal surfaces.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-dichlorobenzene] Data from human exposure to 1,2-dichlorobenzene shows that concentrations of 100 ppm have been reported to cause sporadic irritation of the eyes and respiratory tract.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-2-dichlorobenzene] The Occupational Safety and Health Administration and the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health have set occupational exposure limits at a ceiling of 50 ppm, over an eight-hour workday.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-chloronaphthalene] 1-Chloronaphthalene is obtained directly by chlorination of naphthalene, with the formation of more highly substituted derivatives such as dichloro- and trichloronaphthalenes in addition to the two monochlorinated isomeric compounds: 1-chloronaphthalene and 2-chloronaphthalene.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-chloronaphthalene] This toxic, nonpolar organochlorine compound is sometimes used as a powerful biocide, and is also known as Basileum.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-chloronaphthalene] It occasionally serves as insecticide and fungicide in the timber floors of shipping containers, where it fulfills the same role as chlordane.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-chloronaphthalene] 1-Chloronaphthalene was also used as a common solvent for oils, fats and DDT until the 1970s.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-chloronaphthalene] It is also used to determine the refractive index of crystals.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-methylnaphthalene] 1-Methylnaphthalene defines the lower (zero) reference point of cetane number, a measure of diesel fuel ignition quality, as it has a long ignition delay (poor ignition qualities).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-methylnaphthalene] In contrast, cetane, with its short ignition delay, defines the upper reference point at 100.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-methylnaphthalene] In testing, isocetane (2,2,4,4,6,8,8-heptamethylnonane or HMN) replaced 1-methylnaphthalene as the low cetane number reference fuel in 1962 for reasons of better oxidation stability and ease of use in the reference engine.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-methylnaphthalene] The scale is unchanged, as isocetane's cetane number is measured at 15, referenced to 1-methylnaphthalene and cetane.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-methylnaphthalene] With alkali metals, 1-methylnaphthalene forms radical anion salts such as sodium 1-methylnaphthalene.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-methylnaphthalene] Compared to its structural analog sodium naphthalene, sodium 1-methylnaphthalene is more soluble, which is useful for low-temperature reductions.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/1-methylnaphthalene] The LD50 for 1-methylnaphthalene is low, being 2800 mg/kg (rats).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/2-3-dichloro-5-6-dicyano-1-4-benzoquinone] Synthesis of DDQ involves cyanation of chloranil.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/2-3-dichloro-5-6-dicyano-1-4-benzoquinone] Günther first reported a 6-step preparation in 1906.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/2-3-dichloro-5-6-dicyano-1-4-benzoquinone] The substance did not receive interest until its potential as a dehydrogenation agent was discovered.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/2-3-dichloro-5-6-dicyano-1-4-benzoquinone] A single-step chlorination from 2,3-dicyanohydroquinone was reported in 1965.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/2-3-dichloro-5-6-dicyano-1-4-benzoquinone] The reagent removes pairs of H atoms from organic molecules.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/2-3-dichloro-5-6-dicyano-1-4-benzoquinone] The resulting hydroquinone is poorly soluble in typical reaction solvents (dioxane, benzene, alkanes), which facilitates workup.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/2-3-dichloro-5-6-dicyano-1-4-benzoquinone] Solutions of DDQ in benzene are red, due to the formation of a charge-transfer complex.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/2-3-dichloro-5-6-dicyano-1-4-benzoquinone] DDQ reacts with water to release highly toxic hydrogen cyanide (HCN).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) has listed acetaldehyde as a Group 1 carcinogen.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxins with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] In 1835, Liebig named it "aldehyde", and in the middle of the century the name was altered to "acetaldehyde".
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] In 2013, global production was about 438,000 tonnes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Before 1962, ethanol and acetylene were the major sources of acetaldehyde.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Since then, ethylene is the dominant feedstock.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] In the 1970s, the world capacity of the Wacker-Hoechst direct oxidation process exceeded two million tonnes annually.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Smaller quantities can be prepared by the partial oxidation of ethanol in an exothermic reaction.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] This process typically is conducted over a silver catalyst at about 500–650 °C (950–1,200 °F).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] This method is one of the oldest routes for the industrial preparation of acetaldehyde.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Prior to the Wacker process and the availability of cheap ethylene, acetaldehyde was produced by the hydration of acetylene.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The mechanism involves the intermediacy of vinyl alcohol, which tautomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The reaction is conducted at 90–95 °C (194–203 °F), and the acetaldehyde formed is separated from water and mercury and cooled to 25–30 °C (77–86 °F).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] In the wet oxidation process, iron(III) sulfate is used to reoxidize the mercury back to the mercury(II) salt.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The resulting iron(II) sulfate is oxidized in a separate reactor with nitric acid.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The enzyme Acetylene hydratase discovered in the strictly anaerobic bacterium *Pelobacter acetylenicus* can catalyze an analogous reaction without involving any compounds of mercury.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] However, it has thus far not been brought to any large-scale or commercial use.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] In this endothermic process, ethanol vapor is passed at 260–290 °C over a copper-based catalyst.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The process was once attractive because of the value of the hydrogen coproduct, but in modern times is not economically viable.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The hydroformylation of methanol with catalysts like cobalt, nickel, or iron salts also produces acetaldehyde, although this process is of no industrial importance.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Similarly noncompetitive, acetaldehyde arises from synthesis gas with modest selectivity.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The equilibrium constant is 6×10−7 at room temperature, thus that the relative amount of the enol form in a sample of acetaldehyde is very small.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] At room temperature, acetaldehyde (CH3CH=O) is more stable than vinyl alcohol (CH2=CHOH) by 42.7 kJ/mol: Overall the keto-enol tautomerization occurs slowly but is catalyzed by acids.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Photo-induced keto-enol tautomerization is viable under atmospheric or stratospheric conditions.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] This photo-tautomerization is relevant to the Earth's atmosphere, because vinyl alcohol is thought to be a precursor to carboxylic acids in the atmosphere.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a common electrophile in organic synthesis.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] In addition reactions acetaldehyde is prochiral.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] It is used primarily as a source of the "CH3C+H(OH)" synthon in aldol reactions and related condensation reactions.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Grignard reagents and organolithium compounds react with MeCHO to give hydroxyethyl derivatives.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] In one of the more spectacular addition reactions, formaldehyde in the presence of calcium hydroxide adds to MeCHO to give pentaerythritol, C(CH2OH)4 and formate.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] In a Strecker reaction, acetaldehyde condenses with cyanide and ammonia to give, after hydrolysis, the amino acid alanine.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can condense with amines to yield imines; for example, with cyclohexylamine to give *N*-ethylidenecyclohexylamine.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] These imines can be used to direct subsequent reactions like an aldol condensation.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] It is also a building block in the synthesis of heterocyclic compounds.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] In one example, it converts, upon treatment with ammonia, to 5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine ("aldehyde-collidine").
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Three molecules of acetaldehyde condense to form "paraldehyde", a cyclic trimer containing C-O single bonds.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Similarly condensation of four molecules of acetaldehyde give the cyclic molecule metaldehyde.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Paraldehyde can be produced in good yields, using a sulfuric acid catalyst.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Metaldehyde is only obtained in a few percent yield and with cooling, often using HBr rather than H2SO4 as the catalyst.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] At −40 °C (−40 °F) in the presence of acid catalysts, polyacetaldehyde is produced.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] There are two stereomers of paraldehyde and four of metaldehyde.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The German chemist Valentin Hermann Weidenbusch (1821–1893) synthesized paraldehyde in 1848 by treating acetaldehyde with acid (either sulfuric or nitric acid) and cooling to 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] He found it quite remarkable that when paraldehyde was *heated* with a trace of the same acid, the reaction went the other way, recreating acetaldehyde.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Although vinyl alcohol is a tautomeric form of acetaldehyde (§ Tautomerization to vinyl alcohol), polyvinyl alcohol cannot be produced from acetaldehyde.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde forms a stable acetal upon reaction with ethanol under conditions that favor dehydration.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The product, CH3CH(OCH2CH3)2, is formally named 1,1-diethoxyethane but is commonly referred to as "acetal".
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] This can cause confusion as "acetal" is more commonly used to describe compounds with the functional groups RCH(OR')2 or RR'C(OR'')2 rather than referring to this specific compound — in fact, 1,1-diethoxyethane is also described as the diethyl acetal of acetaldehyde.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a precursor to vinylphosphonic acid, which is used to make adhesives and ion conductive membranes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] In the liver, the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase oxidizes ethanol into acetaldehyde, which is then further oxidized into harmless acetic acid by acetaldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] These two oxidation reactions are coupled with the reduction of NAD+ to NADH.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] In the brain, the enzyme catalase is primarily responsible for oxidizing ethanol to acetaldehyde, and alcohol dehydrogenase plays a minor role.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The last steps of alcoholic fermentation in bacteria, plants, and yeast involve the conversion of pyruvate into acetaldehyde and carbon dioxide by the enzyme pyruvate decarboxylase, followed by the conversion of acetaldehyde into ethanol.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The latter reaction is again catalyzed by an alcohol dehydrogenase, now operating in the opposite direction.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Many East Asian people have an ALDH2 mutation which makes them significantly less efficient at oxidizing acetaldehyde.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] On consuming alcohol, their bodies tend to accumulate excessive amounts of acetaldehyde, causing the so-called alcohol flush reaction.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] They develop a characteristic flush on the face and body, along with "nausea, headache and general physical discomfort".
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Ingestion of the drug disulfiram, which inhibits ALDH2, leads to a similar reaction .
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Traditionally, acetaldehyde was mainly used as a precursor to acetic acid.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] This application has declined because acetic acid is produced more efficiently from methanol by the Monsanto and Cativa processes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an important precursor to pyridine derivatives, pentaerythritol, and crotonaldehyde.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Urea and acetaldehyde combine to give a useful resin.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetic anhydride reacts with acetaldehyde to give ethylidene diacetate, a precursor to vinyl acetate, which is used to produce polyvinyl acetate.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The global market for acetaldehyde is declining.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Demand has been impacted by changes in the production of plasticizer alcohols, which has shifted because *n*-butyraldehyde is less often produced from acetaldehyde, instead being generated by hydroformylation of propylene.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Likewise, acetic acid, once produced from acetaldehyde, is made predominantly by the lower-cost methanol carbonylation process.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The impact on demand has led to increase in prices and thus slowdown in the market.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] China is the largest consumer of acetaldehyde in the world, accounting for almost half of global consumption in 2012.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Major use has been the production of acetic acid.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Other uses such as pyridines and pentaerythritol are expected to grow faster than acetic acid, but the volumes are not large enough to offset the decline in acetic acid.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] As a consequence, overall acetaldehyde consumption in China may grow slightly at 1.6% per year through 2018.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Western Europe is the second-largest consumer of acetaldehyde worldwide, accounting for 20% of world consumption in 2012.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] As with China, the Western European acetaldehyde market is expected to increase only very slightly at 1% per year during 2012–2018.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] However, Japan could emerge as a potential consumer for acetaldehyde in the next five years due to newfound use in commercial production of butadiene.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The supply of butadiene has been volatile in Japan and the rest of Asia.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] This should provide the much needed boost to the flat market, as of 2013.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The threshold limit value is 25 ppm (STEL/ceiling value) and the MAK (Maximum Workplace Concentration) is 50 ppm.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] At 50 ppm acetaldehyde, no irritation or local tissue damage in the nasal mucosa is observed.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] When taken up by the organism, acetaldehyde is metabolized rapidly in the liver to acetic acid.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Only a small proportion is exhaled unchanged.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] After intravenous injection, the half-life in the blood is approximately 90 seconds.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Many serious cases of acute intoxication have been recorded.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde naturally breaks down in the human body.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an irritant of the skin, eyes, mucous membranes, throat, and respiratory tract.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] This occurs at concentrations as low as 1000 ppm.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Symptoms of exposure to this compound include nausea, vomiting, and headache.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] These symptoms may not happen immediately.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The perception threshold for acetaldehyde in air is in the range between 0.07 and 0.25 ppm.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] At such concentrations, the fruity odor of acetaldehyde is apparent.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Conjunctival irritations have been observed after a 15-minute exposure to concentrations of 25 and 50 ppm, but transient conjunctivitis and irritation of the respiratory tract have been reported after exposure to 200 ppm acetaldehyde for 15 minutes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] In addition, acetaldehyde is damaging to DNA and causes abnormal muscle development as it binds to proteins.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde induces DNA interstrand crosslinks, a form of DNA damage.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] These can be repaired by either of two replication-coupled DNA repair pathways.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The first is referred to as the FA pathway, because it employs gene products defective in Fanconi's anemia patients.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] This repair pathway results in increased mutation frequency and altered mutational spectrum.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The second repair pathway requires replication fork convergence, breakage of the acetaldehyde crosslink, translesion synthesis by a Y-family DNA polymerase and homologous recombination.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] People with a genetic deficiency for the enzyme responsible for the conversion of acetaldehyde into acetic acid may have a greater risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] A study of 818 heavy drinkers found that those exposed to more acetaldehyde than normal through a genetic variant of the gene encoding for ADH1C, ADH1C*1, are at greater risk of developing cancers of the upper gastrointestinal tract and liver.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The drug disulfiram (Antabuse) inhibits acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, an enzyme that oxidizes the compound into acetic acid.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Metabolism of ethanol forms acetaldehyde before acetaldehyde dehydrogenase forms acetic acid, but with the enzyme inhibited, acetaldehyde accumulates.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] If one consumes ethanol while taking disulfiram, the hangover effect of ethanol is felt more rapidly and intensely (disulfiram-alcohol reaction).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] As such, disulfiram is sometimes used as a deterrent for alcoholics wishing to stay sober.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a potential contaminant in workplace, indoors, and ambient environments.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Moreover, the majority of humans spend more than 90% of their time in indoor environments, increasing any exposure and the risk to human health.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] In a study in France, the mean indoor concentration of acetaldehydes measured in 16 homes was approximately seven times higher than the outside acetaldehyde concentration.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The living room had a mean of 18.1±17.5 μg m−3 and the bedroom was 18.2±16.9 μg m−3, whereas the outdoor air had a mean concentration of 2.3±2.6 μg m−3.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] It has been concluded that volatile organic compounds (VOC) such as benzene, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, toluene, and xylenes have to be considered priority pollutants with respect to their health effects.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] It has been pointed that in renovated or completely new buildings, the VOCs concentration levels are often several orders of magnitude higher.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The main sources of acetaldehydes in homes include building materials, laminate, PVC flooring, varnished wood flooring, and varnished cork/pine flooring (found in the varnish, not the wood).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] It is also found in plastics, oil-based and water-based paints, in composite wood ceilings, particle-board, plywood, treated pine wood, and laminated chipboard furniture.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The use of acetaldehyde is widespread in different industries, and it may be released into waste water or the air during production, use, transportation and storage.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Sources of acetaldehyde include fuel combustion emissions from stationary internal combustion engines and power plants that burn fossil fuels, wood, or trash, oil and gas extraction, refineries, cement kilns, lumber and wood mills and paper mills.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also present in automobile and diesel exhaust.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] As a result, acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxics with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Natural tobacco polysaccharides, including cellulose, have been shown to be the primary precursors making acetaldehyde a significant constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] It has been demonstrated to have a synergistic effect with nicotine in rodent studies of addiction.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also the most abundant carcinogen in tobacco smoke; it is dissolved into the saliva while smoking.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde has been found in cannabis smoke.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] This finding emerged through the use of new chemical techniques that demonstrated the acetaldehyde present was causing DNA damage in laboratory settings.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Many microbes produce acetaldehyde from ethanol, but they have a lower capacity to eliminate the acetaldehyde, which can lead to the accumulation of acetaldehyde in saliva, stomach acid, and intestinal contents.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Fermented food and many alcoholic beverages can also contain significant amounts of acetaldehyde.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde, derived from mucosal or microbial oxidation of ethanol, tobacco smoke, and diet, appears to act as a cumulative carcinogen in the upper digestive tract of humans.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] According to European Commission's Scientific Committee on Consumer Safety's (SCCS) "Opinion on Acetaldehyde" (2012) the cosmetic products special risk limit is 5 mg/L and acetaldehyde should not be used in mouth-washing products.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can be produced by the photo-oxidation of polyethylene terephthalate (PET), via a Type II Norrish reaction.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] Although the levels produced by this process are minute acetaldehyde has an exceedingly low taste/odor threshold of around 20–40 ppb and can cause an off-taste in bottled water.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The level at which an average consumer could detect acetaldehyde is still considerably lower than any toxicity.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/acetaldehyde] The yeast *Candida albicans* in patients with potentially carcinogenic oral diseases has been shown to produce acetaldehyde in quantities sufficient to cause problems.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Buckminsterfullerene is a black solid that dissolves in hydrocarbon solvents to produce a purple solution.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The substance was discovered in 1985 and has received intense study, although few real world applications have been found.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Molecules of buckminsterfullerene (or of fullerenes in general) are commonly nicknamed **buckyballs**.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Buckminsterfullerene is the most common naturally occurring fullerene.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Small quantities of it can be found in soot.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Neutral C 60 has been observed in planetary nebulae and several types of star.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The ionised form, C+ 60, has been identified in the interstellar medium, where it is the cause of several absorption features known as diffuse interstellar bands in the near-infrared.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Theoretical predictions of buckminsterfullerene molecules appeared in the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] It was first generated in 1984 by Eric Rohlfing, Donald Cox, and Andrew Kaldor, using a laser to vaporize carbon in a supersonic helium beam, although the group did not realize that buckminsterfullerene had been produced.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] In 1985 their work was repeated by Harold Kroto, James R.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] O'Brien, Robert Curl, and Richard Smalley at Rice University, who recognized the structure of C 60 as buckminsterfullerene.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Concurrent but unconnected to the Kroto-Smalley work, astrophysicists were working with spectroscopists to study infrared emissions from giant red carbon stars.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Smalley and team were able to use a laser vaporization technique to create carbon clusters which could potentially emit infrared at the same wavelength as had been emitted by the red carbon star.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Hence, the inspiration came to Smalley and team to use the laser technique on graphite to generate fullerenes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Using laser evaporation of graphite the Smalley team found C*n* clusters (where *n* > 20 and even) of which the most common were C 60 and C 70.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] A solid rotating graphite disk was used as the surface from which carbon was vaporized using a laser beam creating hot plasma that was then passed through a stream of high-density helium gas.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The carbon species were subsequently cooled and ionized resulting in the formation of clusters.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Clusters ranged in molecular masses, but Kroto and Smalley found predominance in a C 60 cluster that could be enhanced further by allowing the plasma to react longer.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] They also discovered that C 60 is a cage-like molecule, a regular truncated icosahedron.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The experimental evidence, a strong peak at 720 daltons, indicated that a carbon molecule with 60 carbon atoms was forming, but provided no structural information.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The research group concluded after reactivity experiments, that the most likely structure was a spheroidal molecule.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The idea was quickly rationalized as the basis of an icosahedral symmetry closed cage structure.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Kroto, Curl, and Smalley were awarded the 1996 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their roles in the discovery of buckminsterfullerene and the related class of molecules, the fullerenes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] In 1989 physicists Wolfgang Krätschmer, Konstantinos Fostiropoulos, and Donald R.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Huffman observed unusual optical absorptions in thin films of carbon dust (soot).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The soot had been generated by an arc-process between two graphite electrodes in a helium atmosphere where the electrode material evaporates and condenses forming soot in the quenching atmosphere.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Among other features, the IR spectra of the soot showed four discrete bands in close agreement to those proposed for C 60.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Another paper on the characterization and verification of the molecular structure followed on in the same year (1990) from their thin film experiments, and detailed also the extraction of an evaporable as well as benzene-soluble material from the arc-generated soot.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] This extract had TEM and X-ray crystal analysis consistent with arrays of spherical C 60 molecules, approximately 1.0 nm in van der Waals diameter as well as the expected molecular mass of 720 Da for C 60 (and 840 Da for C 70) in their mass spectra.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The method was simple and efficient to prepare the material in gram amounts per day (1990) which has boosted the fullerene research and is even today applied for the commercial production of fullerenes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The discovery of practical routes to C 60 led to the exploration of a new field of chemistry involving the study of fullerenes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The discoverers of the allotrope named the newfound molecule after American architect R.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Buckminster Fuller, who designed many geodesic dome structures that look similar to C 60 and who had died in 1983, the year before discovery.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Another common name for buckminsterfullerene is "buckyballs".
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Soot is produced by laser ablation of graphite or pyrolysis of aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Fullerenes are extracted from the soot with organic solvents using a Soxhlet extractor.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] This step yields a solution containing up to 75% of C 60, as well as other fullerenes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] These fractions are separated using chromatography.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Generally, the fullerenes are dissolved in a hydrocarbon or halogenated hydrocarbon and separated using alumina columns.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Synthesis using the techniques of "classical organic chemistry" is possible, but not economic.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The van der Waals diameter of a C 60 molecule is about 1.01 nanometers (nm).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The nucleus to nucleus diameter of a C 60 molecule is about 0.71 nm.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The 6:6 ring bonds (between two hexagons) can be considered "double bonds" and are shorter than the 6:5 bonds (between a hexagon and a pentagon).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Each carbon atom in the structure is bonded covalently with 3 others.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] A carbon atom in the C 60 can be substituted by a nitrogen or boron atom yielding a C 59N or C 59B respectively.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] For a time buckminsterfullerene was the largest known molecule observed to exhibit wave–particle duality.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] In 2020 the dye molecule phthalocyanine exhibited the duality that is more famously attributed to light, electrons and other small particles and molecules.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Fullerenes are sparingly soluble in aromatic solvents and carbon disulfide, but insoluble in water.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Solutions of pure C 60 have a deep purple color which leaves a brown residue upon evaporation.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The reason for this color change is the relatively narrow energy width of the band of molecular levels responsible for green light absorption by individual C 60 molecules.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Thus individual molecules transmit some blue and red light resulting in a purple color.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Upon drying, intermolecular interaction results in the overlap and broadening of the energy bands, thereby eliminating the blue light transmittance and causing the purple to brown color change.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] C 60 crystallises with some solvents in the lattice ("solvates").
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] For example, crystallization of C 60 from benzene solution yields triclinic crystals with the formula C60·4C6H6.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Like other solvates, this one readily releases benzene to give the usual face-centred cubic C 60.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Millimeter-sized crystals of C 60 and C 70 can be grown from solution both for solvates and for pure fullerenes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] In solid buckminsterfullerene, the C 60 molecules adopt the fcc (face-centered cubic) motif.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] This change is associated with a first-order phase transition to an fcc structure and a small, yet abrupt increase in the lattice constant from 1.411 to 1.4154 nm.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] C 60 solid is as soft as graphite, but when compressed to less than 70% of its volume it transforms into a superhard form of diamond (see aggregated diamond nanorod).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] C 60 films and solution have strong non-linear optical properties; in particular, their optical absorption increases with light intensity (saturable absorption).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] C 60 forms a brownish solid with an optical absorption threshold at ≈1.6 eV.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] It is an n-type semiconductor with a low activation energy of 0.1–0.3 eV; this conductivity is attributed to intrinsic or oxygen-related defects.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Fcc C 60 contains voids at its octahedral and tetrahedral sites which are sufficiently large (0.6 and 0.2 nm respectively) to accommodate impurity atoms.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] When alkali metals are doped into these voids, C 60 converts from a semiconductor into a conductor or even superconductor.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] C 60 undergoes six reversible, one-electron reductions, ultimately generating C6− 60.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The first reduction occurs at ≈−1.0 V (Fc/Fc+ ), showing that C 60 is a reluctant electron acceptor.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] C 60 tends to avoid having double bonds in the pentagonal rings, which makes electron delocalization poor, and results in C 60 not being "superaromatic".
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] C 60 behaves like an electron deficient alkene.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] For example, it reacts with some nucleophiles.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] C 60 exhibits a small degree of aromatic character, but it still reflects localized double and single C–C bond characters.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Therefore, C 60 can undergo addition with hydrogen to give polyhydrofullerenes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] For example, C 60 reacts with lithium in liquid ammonia, followed by *tert*-butanol to give a mixture of polyhydrofullerenes such as C60H18, C60H32, C60H36, with C60H32 being the dominating product.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] This mixture of polyhydrofullerenes can be re-oxidized by 2,3-dichloro-5,6-dicyano-1,4-benzoquinone to give C 60 again.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] A selective hydrogenation method exists.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Reaction of C 60 with 9,9′,10,10′-dihydroanthracene under the same conditions, depending on the time of reaction, gives C60H32 and C60H18 respectively and selectively.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Addition of fluorine, chlorine, and bromine occurs for C 60.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Fluorine atoms are small enough for a 1,2-addition, while Cl 2 and Br 2 add to remote C atoms due to steric factors.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] For example, in C60Br8 and C60Br24, the Br atoms are in 1,3- or 1,4-positions with respect to each other.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Under various conditions a vast number of halogenated derivatives of C 60 can be produced, some with an extraordinary selectivity on one or two isomers over the other possible ones.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Addition of fluorine and chlorine usually results in a flattening of the C 60 framework into a drum-shaped molecule.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Solutions of C 60 can be oxygenated to the epoxide C60O.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Ozonation of C 60 in 1,2-xylene at 257K gives an intermediate ozonide C60O3, which can be decomposed into 2 forms of C60O.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Decomposition of C60O3 at 296 K gives the epoxide, but photolysis gives a product in which the O atom bridges a 5,6-edge.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The Diels–Alder reaction is commonly employed to functionalize C 60.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Reaction of C 60 with appropriate substituted diene gives the corresponding adduct.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The Diels–Alder reaction between C 60 and 3,6-diaryl-1,2,4,5-tetrazines affordsC 62.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The C 62 has the structure in which a four-membered ring is surrounded by four six-membered rings.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The C 60 molecules can also be coupled through a [2+2] cycloaddition, giving the dumbbell-shaped compound C 120.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The coupling is achieved by high-speed vibrating milling of C 60 with a catalytic amount of KCN.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The reaction is reversible as C 120 dissociates back to two C 60 molecules when heated at 450 K (177 °C; 350 °F).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Under high pressure and temperature, repeated [2+2] cycloaddition between C 60 results in polymerized fullerene chains and networks.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] These polymers remain stable at ambient pressure and temperature once formed, and have remarkably interesting electronic and magnetic properties, such as being ferromagnetic above room temperature.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Reactions of C 60 with free radicals readily occur.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] When C 60 is mixed with a disulfide RSSR, the radical C60SR• forms spontaneously upon irradiation of the mixture.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Stability of the radical species C60Y• depends largely on steric factors of Y.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Cyclopropanation (the Bingel reaction) is another common method for functionalizing C 60.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Cyclopropanation of C 60 mostly occurs at the junction of 2 hexagons due to steric factors.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The first cyclopropanation was carried out by treating the β-bromomalonate with C 60 in the presence of a base.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Cyclopropanation also occur readily with diazomethanes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] For example, diphenyldiazomethane reacts readily with C 60 to give the compound C61Ph2.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Phenyl-C 61-butyric acid methyl ester derivative prepared through cyclopropanation has been studied for use in organic solar cells.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The LUMO in C 60 is triply degenerate, with the HOMO–LUMO separation relatively small.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] This small gap suggests that reduction of C 60 should occur at mild potentials leading to fulleride anions, [C60]*n*− (*n* = 1–6).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] This salt exhibits ferromagnetism at 16 K.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Three reversible oxidation processes have been observed by using cyclic voltammetry with ultra-dry methylene chloride and a supporting electrolyte with extremely high oxidation resistance and low nucleophilicity, such as [nBu4N][AsF6].
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] C 60 forms complexes akin to the more common alkenes.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Complexes have been reported molybdenum, tungsten, platinum, palladium, iridium, and titanium.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The pentacarbonyl species are produced by photochemical reactions.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] One such iridium complex, [Ir(η2-C60)(CO)Cl(Ph2CH2C6H4OCH2Ph)2] has been prepared where the metal center projects two electron-rich 'arms' that embrace the C 60 guest.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Metal atoms or certain small molecules such as H 2 and noble gas can be encapsulated inside the C 60 cage.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] These endohedral fullerenes are usually synthesized by doping in the metal atoms in an arc reactor or by laser evaporation.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] These methods gives low yields of endohedral fullerenes, and a better method involves the opening of the cage, packing in the atoms or molecules, and closing the opening using certain organic reactions.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] This method, however, is still immature and only a few species have been synthesized this way.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Endohedral fullerenes show distinct and intriguing chemical properties that can be completely different from the encapsulated atom or molecule, as well as the fullerene itself.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The encapsulated atoms have been shown to perform circular motions inside the C 60 cage, and their motion has been followed using NMR spectroscopy.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Predictions of boron fullerenes began in 2007 when researchers Nevill Szwacki, Arta Sadrzadeh, and Boris Yakobson from Rice University proposed a stable cage of 80 boron atoms with the same structure as C60 but with an additional boron atom at the center of each hexagon.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The existence of the B80 fullerene was debated, as subsequent density functional theory calculations found it to be significantly less stable than other configurations of 80 boron atoms; this may be due to errors in the calculated bond lengths.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] A smaller configuration of 40 boron atoms (borospherene) was observed in 2014, however it lacked the icosahedral symmetry of C60.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The B80 buckyball was first observed in 2026 by a team led by Lai-Sheng Wang at Brown University, using a laser to vaporize a boron target in a helium carrier gas mixed with argon to cool the resulting clusters.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The photoelectron spectrum of the B80− anion showed a few sharp peaks, indicating a symmetric structure.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Of the candidate structures, only the simulated spectrum of the buckyball agreed with the experimental result.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The optical absorption properties of C 60 match the solar spectrum in a way that suggests that C 60-based films could be useful for photovoltaic applications.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Because of its high electronic affinity it is one of the most common electron acceptors used in donor/acceptor based solar cells.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Conversion efficiencies up to 5.7% have been reported in C 60–polymer cells.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] C 60 is sensitive to light, so leaving C 60 under light exposure causes it to degrade, becoming dangerous.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] The ingestion of C 60 solutions that have been exposed to light could lead to developing cancer (tumors).
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Otherwise, a study found that C 60 remains in the body for a longer time than usual, especially in the liver, where it tends to be accumulated, and therefore has the potential to induce detrimental health effects.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] C 60 in olive oil administered to mice resulted in no extension in lifespan.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] C 60 in olive oil administered to beagle dogs resulted in a large reduction of C-reactive protein, which is commonly elevated in cardiovascular disease and cerebrovascular disease.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Many oils with C 60 have been sold as antioxidant products, but it does not avoid the problem of their sensitivity to light, that can turn them toxic.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] A later research confirmed that exposure to light degrades solutions of C 60 in oil, making it toxic and leading to a "massive" increase of the risk of developing cancer (tumors) after its consumption.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] To avoid the degradation by effect of light, C 60 oils must be made in very dark environments, encased into bottles of great opacity, and kept in darkness, consumed under low light conditions and accompanied by labels to warn about the dangers of light for C 60.
[src:buckminsterfullerene/buckminsterfullerene] Some producers have been able to dissolve C 60 in water to avoid possible problems with oils, but that would not protect C 60 from light, so the same cautions are needed.
